01:08:49,812 --> 01:08:51,727
Get the yard to sign off on it.

768
01:08:52,783 --> 01:08:53,934
You mean Don.

769
01:08:54,388 --> 01:08:56,039
That's who's in charge.

770
01:09:02,872 --> 01:09:05,123
Sorry, ma'am.
No women on the lot.

771
01:09:05,696 --> 01:09:07,401
My name is Temple Grandin.

772
01:09:07,527 --> 01:09:10,216
- I'm a grad student at Arizona State.
- That's the rules.

773
01:09:11,323 --> 01:09:14,304
I'm a grad student at Arizona State
and I was here last week.

774
01:09:14,473 --> 01:09:17,351
Complaints from cowboys' wives.
They don't want no women.

775
01:09:17,952 --> 01:09:19,271
I'm just doin' my job.

776
01:09:23,820 --> 01:09:25,725
Ma'am, you're holdin' up the line.

777
01:09:25,850 --> 01:09:28,368
You'll have to turn around
and take it on off the lot.

778
01:09:28,493 --> 01:09:29,343
Please.

779
01:09:33,445 --> 01:09:34,761
Don't come back!

780
01:09:36,805 --> 01:09:39,266
John Richmond, press,
<i>Ranchman Magazine</i>.

781
01:09:39,391 --> 01:09:40,342
Go on in.

782
01:09:49,637 --> 01:09:50,738
<i>It's a door.</i>

783
01:09:51,904 --> 01:09:53,305
<i>It's another door.</i>

784
01:10:05,716 --> 01:10:06,883
Thanks, take care.

785
01:10:43,863 --> 01:10:45,764
- Good mornin'.
- Go on in.

786
01:10:53,566 --> 01:10:55,217
- Mornin'.
- Go on in.

787
01:11:02,250 --> 01:11:03,199
Hi, Sanch.

788
01:11:04,770 --> 01:11:07,435
Good to have you back.
A long time since you worked here.

789
01:11:07,560 --> 01:11:08,601
Yeah, it does.

790
01:11:08,770 --> 01:11:10,681
- What's this, Purple Heart?
- It is.

791
01:11:10,806 --> 01:11:12,311
We're real proud of ya.

792
01:11:12,436 --> 01:11:15,015
Jeez, you didn't get all these
just diggin' latrines.

793
01:11:15,140 --> 01:11:17,363
- No, sir. I was in Khe Sanh.
- Good for you.

794
01:11:17,531 --> 01:11:20,095
Excuse me, sir.
I need you to sign my master's thesis.

795
01:11:20,220 --> 01:11:23,100
- How'd you get in here?
- They just waved me in.

796
01:11:23,774 --> 01:11:25,381
What are you gonna research?

797
01:11:25,506 --> 01:11:27,007
Agitation in cattle.

798
01:11:27,670 --> 01:11:29,297
Would that be mooing?

799
01:11:30,162 --> 01:11:31,635
You believe that crap?

800
01:11:31,760 --> 01:11:34,137
Since cattle are prey animals,
loud mooing is a sign...

801
01:11:34,306 --> 01:11:35,156
No way.

802
01:11:36,825 --> 01:11:38,737
Come on, let's get some coffee.

803
01:11:38,862 --> 01:11:41,146
Did you bring back
a little china gals with ya?

804
01:11:41,271 --> 01:11:44,293
No, they wouldn't let me
bring back one on the airplane.

805
01:11:44,819 --> 01:11:46,947
You girls
got the coffee ready in here?

806
01:11:47,117 --> 01:11:49,827
- We got a man that's thirsty.
- Come on in!

807
01:12:16,041 --> 01:12:18,035
Do you have another entrance?

808
01:12:19,518 --> 01:12:20,369
Pardon?

809
01:12:21,042 --> 01:12:22,846
Do you have another entrance?

810
01:12:23,337 --> 01:12:24,337
No, ma'am.

811
01:12:37,764 --> 01:12:39,569
Do you have any jell-o or yogurt?

812
01:12:39,737 --> 01:12:42,283
In the cooler.
Right behind you, darlin'.

813
01:13:14,746 --> 01:13:16,332
<i>By eating weaker and slower ones,</i>

814
01:13:17,348 --> 01:13:18,918
<i>lions keep antelope population</i>

815
01:13:19,087 --> 01:13:21,643
<i>strong and in proper proportion</i>

816
01:13:21,898 --> 01:13:23,448
<i>to all other animals.</i>

817
01:13:47,973 --> 01:13:49,224
Light.
Shadow.

818
01:14:05,531 --> 01:14:07,132
Reflections on puddle.

819
01:14:48,382 --> 01:14:50,283
I've eaten bulls' testicles!

820
01:14:50,723 --> 01:14:52,692
Ate 'em in my aunt's ranch...

821
01:14:52,817 --> 01:14:53,809
Regularly!

822
01:14:57,816 --> 01:14:59,167
This is a waste!

823
01:15:56,235 --> 01:15:58,438
You gotta remember
to drink out here.

824
01:15:58,984 --> 01:16:01,042
I have data
on things that make 'em balk.

825
01:16:01,167 --> 01:16:02,884
Shadows, reflections on water,

826
01:16:03,009 --> 01:16:05,053
- chain glinting in the sun.
- Is that right?

827
01:16:05,178 --> 01:16:07,759
They won't walk in shaded areas.
They must see where they're goin'.

828
01:16:07,884 --> 01:16:11,487
I've lots of important information,
I need Mr. Michaels to sign off on it.

829
01:16:11,678 --> 01:16:13,474
Don?
Don don't sign nothin'.

830
01:16:13,599 --> 01:16:16,217
- I need Mr. Michaels...
- You're not hearin' me.

831
01:16:16,342 --> 01:16:17,992
Don don't sign nothin'.

832
01:16:18,987 --> 01:16:20,988
I sign everything around here.

833
01:16:21,900 --> 01:16:23,201
His signature...

834
01:16:23,769 --> 01:16:25,320
but I do the signin'.

835
01:16:26,636 --> 01:16:28,887
I'm not even sure if Don can write.

836
01:16:31,797 --> 01:16:32,598
Say...

837
01:16:33,209 --> 01:16:35,425
you're interested in cattle
and how they act,

838
01:16:35,550 --> 01:16:37,713
you shouldn't
just hang around feedlots.

839
01:16:38,027 --> 01:16:41,029
You should be out on ranches,
auctions, rodeos...

840
01:16:41,680 --> 01:16:43,131
that sort of thing.

841
01:16:48,689 --> 01:16:50,732
<i>Got the big steer here. 1,000 lbs.</i>

842
01:16:50,926 --> 01:16:53,905
<i>Let's go!
20. 25. 25 and a half.</i>

843
01:16:54,074 --> 01:16:56,574
- <i>He's 25 and a half, 75.</i>
- He looks mean.

844
01:16:56,743 --> 01:16:58,953
<i>25, 75. 30. 30.</i>

845
01:16:59,432 --> 01:17:01,373
<i>Sold him on pat 17.</i>

846
01:17:03,390 --> 01:17:06,258
<i>Look at his mama here.
Now, 75, I got 25.</i>

847
01:17:06,521 --> 01:17:08,176
<i>25. 25.
27 and a half.</i>

848
01:17:08,344 --> 01:17:10,404
<i>He's 27. 30.
32 and a half. 35.</i>

849
01:17:10,529 --> 01:17:12,626
<i>Sold 'em.
Pat 21. Pat 21.</i>

850
01:17:29,250 --> 01:17:30,918
A good magazine.
Take a look.

851
01:17:31,086 --> 01:17:33,470
Help you out
with all kinds of cattle questions.

852
01:17:36,886 --> 01:17:39,044
See you back here
in about 5 minutes, OK?

853
01:17:39,573 --> 01:17:40,654
Excuse...

854
01:17:45,608 --> 01:17:47,559
It's all doors to new worlds.

855
01:17:56,931 --> 01:17:58,647
Excuse me, sir?
Sir?

856
01:17:59,128 --> 01:18:02,509
Very pleased to meet you.
Temple Grandin, bachelor of science,

857
01:18:02,634 --> 01:18:04,301
doin' my masters at Arizona State,

858
01:18:04,469 --> 01:18:06,454
studying in Scottsdale feed yards.

859
01:18:06,579 --> 01:18:09,945
I was wondering if I could interest
the <i>Arizona Farmer-Ranchman</i> periodical

860
01:18:10,070 --> 01:18:12,741
on a thesis I'm writing
on control systems and cattle

861
01:18:12,866 --> 01:18:16,169
and why some work better than others
and how they can tell the difference.

862
01:18:17,531 --> 01:18:20,867
How'd you get on with old Don Michaels
over at Scottsdale?

863
01:18:21,906 --> 01:18:24,289
I told him
I've eaten bull testicles, sir.

864
01:18:26,375 --> 01:18:28,708
I will read anything
you send in, Miss Grandin.

865
01:18:29,130 --> 01:18:31,175
In fact, here...
Take my card.

866
01:18:32,124 --> 01:18:33,963
You address it directly to me.

867
01:18:41,732 --> 01:18:42,733
It's open.

868
01:18:43,777 --> 01:18:47,505
Sir, Scottsdale feedlot signed off
on my cattle agitation study.

869
01:18:47,756 --> 01:18:49,910
Smells like half the herd
signed it first.

870
01:18:51,705 --> 01:18:53,460
No, sir.
Cattle can't do that.

871
01:18:53,585 --> 01:18:56,255
And I don't need the magazine.
I'm a subscriber.

872
01:18:56,639 --> 01:18:58,750
I just wanna make sure
you saw my article

873
01:18:58,875 --> 01:19:01,032
on mooing as a guide
to cattle agitation.

874
01:19:01,254 --> 01:19:04,814
Full thesis is still at the typist,
but you should have it by Friday.

875
01:19:17,354 --> 01:19:18,204
Well...

876
01:19:18,534 --> 01:19:19,935
Master of science.

877
01:19:20,540 --> 01:19:22,496
Master of science
and animal science.

878
01:19:22,621 --> 01:19:25,463
Fantastic.
I bet you're glad to be back east.

879
01:19:26,040 --> 01:19:28,467
- I like the west.
- Oh, so do I,

880
01:19:28,635 --> 01:19:30,095
but it isn't home, is it?

881
01:19:30,263 --> 01:19:33,869
What will you do with your masters?
Your mother mentioned teaching maybe.

882
01:19:33,994 --> 01:19:36,043
Great new school
over West Medford way.

883
01:19:36,168 --> 01:19:38,869
I have a lot of more research to do
and things to write.

884
01:19:38,994 --> 01:19:40,652
Right, you've been published.

885
01:19:40,820 --> 01:19:42,271
You remember Scott?

886
01:19:44,159 --> 01:19:45,159
Over here.

887
01:19:45,353 --> 01:19:47,152
- Be right back.
- Our oldest boy.

888
01:19:47,277 --> 01:19:49,958
New York Magazine's
taken a piece of his.

889
01:19:50,427 --> 01:19:51,878
You remember Scott?

890
01:19:52,338 --> 01:19:54,298
He used to spit in my jell-o.

891
01:19:54,466 --> 01:19:55,917
I'm sure he didn't.

892
01:19:57,678 --> 01:19:59,415
Tell Scott about your writing.

893
01:20:00,157 --> 01:20:03,841
I published two articles
in the <i>Arizona Farmer-Ranchman</i>.

894
01:20:04,348 --> 01:20:06,274
- The Ariz...
- <i>Arizona Farmer-Ranchman</i>.

895
01:20:07,201 --> 01:20:09,445
One was on good moos and bad moos.

896
01:20:09,613 --> 01:20:13,074
The other was on head restraints
and cattle chutes and killing pens.

897
01:20:13,243 --> 01:20:15,501
Really badly designed.
Just terrible systems.

898
01:20:15,708 --> 01:20:16,559
Just...

899
01:20:18,192 --> 01:20:20,295
It's lovely to see you, Temple.

900
01:20:21,133 --> 01:20:21,933
Bye.

901
01:20:22,836 --> 01:20:24,136
Merry Christmas.

902
01:20:25,655 --> 01:20:26,956
Merry Christmas!

903
01:20:29,059 --> 01:20:30,860
I need my squeeze machine!

904
01:20:36,149 --> 01:20:37,630
I hate parties!

905
01:20:38,428 --> 01:20:41,368
There are too many people
and no one listens to me.

906
01:20:41,536 --> 01:20:44,585
They keep giving each other looks
and I don't know what they mean.

907
01:20:44,710 --> 01:20:46,495
They're just uncomfortable.

908
01:20:47,733 --> 01:20:49,630
People don't wanna hear all those...

909
01:20:49,798 --> 01:20:52,092
- details about cattle.
- Well, I do.

910
01:20:52,418 --> 01:20:54,069
I wanna be with cattle.

911
01:20:54,194 --> 01:20:55,305
Sweetheart...

912
01:20:55,473 --> 01:20:57,624
I don't want you to avoid people.

913
01:20:58,561 --> 01:21:01,544
- They make me feel bad.
- Then ignore them!

914
01:21:03,671 --> 01:21:07,649
You are the only
Master of science in the room.

915
01:21:09,035 --> 01:21:11,439
And I am so proud of you.

916
01:21:13,357 --> 01:21:14,417
Look at me.

917
01:21:14,585 --> 01:21:15,635
Look at me.

918
01:21:15,919 --> 01:21:17,339
Do you know if people...

919
01:21:17,464 --> 01:21:19,916
tell each other things
with their eyes,

920
01:21:21,701 --> 01:21:23,799
this is me telling you...

921
01:21:24,092 --> 01:21:25,483
that I love you...

922
01:21:25,608 --> 01:21:27,009
and I respect you.

923
01:21:36,192 --> 01:21:38,393
I will never learn how to do that.

924
01:21:40,967 --> 01:21:41,817
I know.

925
01:22:08,731 --> 01:22:09,632
Damn it!

926
01:22:10,950 --> 01:22:12,674
You are not allowed in here.

927
01:22:13,004 --> 01:22:15,758
- I'm doin' research for article.
- We put up with you sneakin' in

928
01:22:15,926 --> 01:22:18,512
when you was at Arizona State,
but you're done.

929
01:22:18,680 --> 01:22:22,121
No college,
no insurance coverage, no access.

930
01:22:35,583 --> 01:22:37,988
There are many articles
I'd like to write for you.

931
01:22:38,113 --> 01:22:41,327
Firstly, how cattle can be introduced
into dip vats on their own accord.

932
01:22:41,452 --> 01:22:43,883
- Secondly...
- Hold on, Miss Grandin.

933
01:22:44,051 --> 01:22:46,901
Firstly, your articles
have been greatly appreciated.

934
01:22:47,026 --> 01:22:48,306
I got a lot of calls.

935
01:22:48,474 --> 01:22:50,184
Folks think you talk sense.

936
01:22:50,309 --> 01:22:53,760
Secondly, I told you
I would read anything that you write.

937
01:22:54,421 --> 01:22:57,695
Thirdly, young lady,
you need another set of clothes

938
01:22:57,863 --> 01:23:00,783
- when you come in town on business.
- I need to be a press person.

939
01:23:00,951 --> 01:23:02,307
Can I get a press pass?

940
01:23:02,432 --> 01:23:04,282
You askin' for a staff job?

941
01:23:05,225 --> 01:23:07,116
I ain't got but four staff,

942
01:23:07,241 --> 01:23:09,629
and two of them
are bookkeeping and distribution.

943
01:23:09,797 --> 01:23:13,279
No, I don't wanna work here.
I wanna be with cattle, I need a pass.

944
01:23:13,926 --> 01:23:15,579
Well, we can do that.

945
01:23:15,704 --> 01:23:17,105
But like I said...

946
01:23:18,406 --> 01:23:20,467
Mary-Anne?
Get in here.

947
01:23:23,443 --> 01:23:24,243
Sir?

948
01:23:25,243 --> 01:23:27,425
How's that workin'
for ya, Miss Grandin?

949
01:23:27,550 --> 01:23:29,751
It doesn't itch.
I like it a lot.

950
01:23:35,669 --> 01:23:36,961
That's my rank.

951
01:23:37,745 --> 01:23:39,507
They'll be able to see that.

952
01:23:43,082 --> 01:23:43,983
Damn it!

953
01:24:00,165 --> 01:24:01,874
Use it, Temple.
You stink.

954
01:24:01,999 --> 01:24:02,999
Thank you.

955
01:24:04,788 --> 01:24:06,289
Miss Temple Grandin?

956
01:24:06,992 --> 01:24:09,854
I'm Ted Gilbert,
from John Wayne's red river feedlot.

957
01:24:09,979 --> 01:24:12,723
- Hello, very pleased to meet you.
- I've been reading your stuff.

958
01:24:13,159 --> 01:24:15,227
How'd you like
to put it into practice?

959
01:24:15,579 --> 01:24:18,731
See, I lost my designer
and I need a new cattle dip.

960
01:24:19,688 --> 01:24:20,889
Can you do it?

961
01:24:21,279 --> 01:24:22,518
It's pretty simple,

962
01:24:22,643 --> 01:24:25,305
but, I gotta present plans
in five days.

963
01:24:26,223 --> 01:24:27,024
Sure!

964
01:25:09,197 --> 01:25:12,770
- Very clever. How did you find this?
- I see things and put 'em together.

965
01:25:13,128 --> 01:25:14,279
And all this?

966
01:25:14,470 --> 01:25:16,935
To lead the cattle in.
Happy to follow a curve

967
01:25:17,060 --> 01:25:18,955
thinking goin' back
where they came from.

968
01:25:19,080 --> 01:25:20,584
- If you say so.
- I do.

969
01:25:20,709 --> 01:25:24,625
- How long will it take you to do it?
- I have two or three more before this.

970
01:25:24,750 --> 01:25:28,112
- But I need it by tomorrow!
- Everybody needs it tomorrow.

971
01:25:33,049 --> 01:25:36,056
- I won't work quicker if you watch.
- I wanna watch.

972
01:26:24,253 --> 01:26:26,880
This here is Red Harris
from <i>Cattle Magazine</i>.

973
01:26:27,048 --> 01:26:28,582
Very nice to meet you, Mr. Harris.

974
01:26:28,707 --> 01:26:32,355
He can't make the grand opening,
so we could give him a sneak preview.

975
01:26:32,480 --> 01:26:35,592
So, Temple, will you put some cattle
through your dip while I'm here?

976
01:26:38,396 --> 01:26:39,847
Hey, open the gate!

977
01:26:45,946 --> 01:26:49,747
So if the handlers walk slowly clockwise
outside the chute,

978
01:26:50,334 --> 01:26:54,249
then the cow will walk counterclockwise
through the chute.

979
01:26:56,125 --> 01:26:58,426
See? They'll just follow that curve.

980
01:27:02,142 --> 01:27:04,562
The cattle just keep calmly walking

981
01:27:04,730 --> 01:27:07,640
thinking they're goin' in circles
and followin' their buddies.

982
01:27:09,104 --> 01:27:10,913
And they're happy to follow a curve

983
01:27:11,038 --> 01:27:14,065
because they think they're going'back
to where they came from.

984
01:27:15,329 --> 01:27:18,089
They're okay because it's grooved
and they know they won't slip.

985
01:27:18,291 --> 01:27:20,684
So when they take the next step,
their center of gravity

986
01:27:20,810 --> 01:27:22,644
makes them drop calmly into the dip

987
01:27:22,769 --> 01:27:24,843
and they just walk
through the water.

988
01:27:38,061 --> 01:27:40,289
I don't usually tell people
what I'm gonna write,

989
01:27:40,414 --> 01:27:43,662
but, Miss Grandin,
this is a masterpiece.

990
01:27:49,839 --> 01:27:52,528
- I don't want you to do that.
- I'm sorry there, Temple.

991
01:27:52,688 --> 01:27:56,264
Now, look, I want you to be dressed in
your best outfit tomorrow mornin', okay?

992
01:28:12,622 --> 01:28:14,207
Just look at this thing.

993
01:28:14,375 --> 01:28:16,977
It'll take us forever
to get them through here.

994
01:28:17,102 --> 01:28:19,014
J.D., I want you
to get the torch and red,

995
01:28:19,139 --> 01:28:21,907
and I want this out, this out,
I want those panels lined up

996
01:28:22,032 --> 01:28:24,021
and we're gonna run 'em straight in.
Come on.

997
01:28:24,146 --> 01:28:25,356
You two come with me.

998
01:28:25,481 --> 01:28:27,592
- Grab the other end of this.
- Now hold on!

999
01:28:28,902 --> 01:28:32,033
Look at this! I mean, look at that!
Who'd build somethin' like that?

1000
01:28:32,950 --> 01:28:35,833
Jess, get me some sheet steel.
We're gonna slide these puppies in here.

1001
01:28:35,958 --> 01:28:38,284
- Where's that sheet steel?
- Hurry up!

1002
01:28:48,442 --> 01:28:49,785
Let's go.
Get up.

1003
01:28:49,910 --> 01:28:52,463
- Put 'em over and get 'em out of here.
- She's here.

1004
01:28:52,588 --> 01:28:56,144
Don't keep worried, boys.
I'll take care of her. Pick it up.

1005
01:29:02,542 --> 01:29:04,448
Some dip you got here.

1006
01:29:10,248 --> 01:29:11,889
Who put steel on that slope?

1007
01:29:12,014 --> 01:29:13,828
Cattle can't walk on steel!

1008
01:29:14,280 --> 01:29:16,632
That's designed
so they'll walk slowly!

1009
01:29:16,757 --> 01:29:19,968
'Scuse me, little miss.
We just had three head drown in here.

1010
01:29:20,265 --> 01:29:24,034
That's your fault! You killed 'em
'cause of your stupidity!

1011
01:29:27,608 --> 01:29:29,819
And why ain't they comin'
through the curved chute?

1012
01:29:29,988 --> 01:29:32,047
That'd take us all day little lady!

1013
01:29:33,029 --> 01:29:34,910
Hey, that's my shirt!

1014
01:29:35,078 --> 01:29:37,279
If it's smooth, they'll follow it!

1015
01:29:37,404 --> 01:29:39,635
If there's stuff on it,
they'll get scared!

1016
01:29:39,760 --> 01:29:41,361
You can't hang things!

1017
01:29:41,997 --> 01:29:44,841
- You wacko!
- Put it all back the way it was!

1018
01:29:45,137 --> 01:29:47,088
Temple, what's goin' on here?

1019
01:29:47,408 --> 01:29:50,816
They killed three cattle
because of their stupidity!

1020
01:29:51,690 --> 01:29:52,941
They ruined it!

1021
01:29:55,916 --> 01:29:57,318
Just a minute!

1022
01:29:59,614 --> 01:30:02,617
Cattle aren't dangerous!
And they're predictable.

1023
01:30:02,786 --> 01:30:05,272
- it's not hard to design...
- What are you doing in California?

1024
01:30:05,397 --> 01:30:08,260
But the cowboys
would rather prod 'em and scare 'em.

1025
01:30:08,385 --> 01:30:09,811
Did you drive all night?

1026
01:30:09,936 --> 01:30:12,282
I designed a dip vat
at John Red River feedlot

1027
01:30:12,592 --> 01:30:14,485
based on the way cattle
see and behave

1028
01:30:14,610 --> 01:30:17,054
and the editor of <i>Cattle Magazine</i>
said it was a masterpiece

1029
01:30:17,180 --> 01:30:20,477
but the cowboys
killed three cows in it. Three...

1030
01:30:21,021 --> 01:30:22,272
in five minutes

1031
01:30:22,397 --> 01:30:24,650
because they wouldn't
follow my design!

1032
01:30:24,818 --> 01:30:27,697
- Would you like to sit down, or...
- I can't protect the cattle...

1033
01:30:27,865 --> 01:30:29,299
Would you like a cup of tea?

1034
01:30:29,424 --> 01:30:32,454
... system from the moment they enter
to the moment they get slaughtered.

1035
01:30:33,241 --> 01:30:37,152
- You're talking about a slaughterhouse?
- Of course they'll be slaughtered.

1036
01:30:37,277 --> 01:30:40,365
Do you think we'd have cattle
if people didn't eat 'em every day?

1037
01:30:40,490 --> 01:30:42,827
They'd just be funny-lookin' animals
in zoos.

1038
01:30:42,952 --> 01:30:45,244
No, we raise them for us.

1039
01:30:45,975 --> 01:30:48,125
That means we owe them some respect.

1040
01:30:49,729 --> 01:30:53,109
Nature is cruel,
but we don't have to be.

1041
01:30:54,089 --> 01:30:57,716
I wouldn't want to have my guts
ripped out by a lion.

1042
01:30:58,026 --> 01:31:01,412
I'd much rather die in a slaughterhouse
if it was done right!

1043
01:31:01,537 --> 01:31:04,813
- It seems to me that you should be...
- We can easily do it in a way

1044
01:31:04,938 --> 01:31:08,413
where they don't feel pain
and they don't get scared.

1045
01:31:08,538 --> 01:31:11,409
- And their cortisol levels...
- Did you hear what I said?

1046
01:31:11,534 --> 01:31:14,011
I think you're the one
who should design the slaughterhouse.

1047
01:31:14,136 --> 01:31:17,771
I know a slaughterhouse that's a mess
and I know exactly how to fix it.

1048
01:31:52,992 --> 01:31:54,093
It's a door.

1049
01:31:54,751 --> 01:31:56,152
It's another door.

1050
01:32:04,841 --> 01:32:06,051
Can I help you?

1051
01:32:06,276 --> 01:32:09,556
Hello, it's very nice to meet you.
I'd like to tour your slaughterhouse.

1052
01:32:09,786 --> 01:32:10,850
Excuse me?

1053
01:32:11,979 --> 01:32:15,197
Hello, it's very nice to meet you.
I'd like to tour your slaughterhouse.

1054
01:32:15,529 --> 01:32:17,121
We don't do tours, ma'am.

1055
01:32:17,361 --> 01:32:19,709
I designed a drip vat
at John Wayne's red river feedlot

1056
01:32:19,834 --> 01:32:23,802
- that the editor of <i>Cattle Magazine</i>...
- Security? Can I get security?

1057
01:32:50,914 --> 01:32:54,225
<i>I'm so sorry to leave this message
on your answering machine,</i>

1058
01:32:54,350 --> 01:32:56,325
but I thought you'd want to know

1059
01:32:56,502 --> 01:32:59,381
that your friend
Dr. Carlock has died.

1060
01:32:59,913 --> 01:33:01,005
I just saw him!

1061
01:33:01,130 --> 01:33:03,345
Apparently, he'd been sick
for some time.

1062
01:33:03,562 --> 01:33:05,262
You can call me anytime.

1063
01:33:06,308 --> 01:33:07,609
Bye, sweetheart.

1064
01:33:09,247 --> 01:33:10,498
I just saw him.

1065
01:33:19,217 --> 01:33:20,718
What are they doing?

1066
01:33:21,957 --> 01:33:23,632
They're paying their respects.

1067
01:33:23,757 --> 01:33:27,338
It's a way of saying
thank you and goodbye.

1068
01:33:28,045 --> 01:33:30,142
I said goodbye when I saw him.

1069
01:33:30,683 --> 01:33:33,472
This is a final chance
to say goodbye.

1070
01:34:49,326 --> 01:34:51,672
- Are you all right?
- I'm leaving now.

1071
01:34:52,190 --> 01:34:54,982
- It isn't over yet.
- I said goodbye when I saw him.

1072
01:34:55,107 --> 01:34:56,358
He's not there.

1073
01:34:59,017 --> 01:35:00,718
I've got him in my mind.

1074
01:35:04,248 --> 01:35:06,049
Do you know where they go?

1075
01:35:08,912 --> 01:35:10,012
No, I don't.

1076
01:35:14,327 --> 01:35:16,028
Okay.
I'm gonna go now.

1077
01:35:27,742 --> 01:35:28,893
Drive safely.

1078
01:35:58,135 --> 01:35:59,686
There you are, ma'am.

1079
01:36:15,352 --> 01:36:17,203
My, that's a pretty blouse.

1080
01:36:18,666 --> 01:36:20,963
I hope you don't mind me sayin' so.

1081
01:36:21,088 --> 01:36:23,552
Some people think I'm forward,
but, if I like somethin',

1082
01:36:23,677 --> 01:36:26,529
I just come right out
and just compliment 'em.

1083
01:36:27,073 --> 01:36:29,974
It's nice to get a compliment,
don't you think?

1084
01:36:30,551 --> 01:36:33,422
Thank you. It's very nice to meet you.
I'm Temple Grandin.

1085
01:36:33,547 --> 01:36:36,248
Well, it's nice to meet you too.
I'm Betty.

1086
01:36:37,883 --> 01:36:39,584
Well then, there we are.

1087
01:36:41,551 --> 01:36:43,437
Are you waitin' to meet somebody?

1088
01:36:43,729 --> 01:36:46,756
No, I have trouble with automatic doors
sometimes when I'm nervous.

1089
01:36:46,882 --> 01:36:48,032
I'm autistic.

1090
01:36:50,198 --> 01:36:54,045
My son is artistic and he's got
the same thing with airplanes.

1091
01:36:54,462 --> 01:36:56,829
Come on.
You just come along with me.

1092
01:36:58,568 --> 01:36:59,979
All right.
Come on.

1093
01:37:00,104 --> 01:37:03,086
And I'll make sure
that they stay open.

1094
01:37:06,054 --> 01:37:09,058
All right? You are safe now.
You're safe.

1095
01:37:17,556 --> 01:37:18,599
My pleasure.

1096
01:37:19,664 --> 01:37:22,527
Are you a horsewoman?
I mean, you know, your shirt?

1097
01:37:22,652 --> 01:37:25,258
I like horses,
but I work with cattle.

1098
01:37:25,703 --> 01:37:28,897
I designed a dip
that <i>Cattle Magazine</i> called brilliant.

1099
01:37:29,022 --> 01:37:32,036
Oh my golly,
my husband read about you.

1100
01:37:32,161 --> 01:37:33,811
He works over at Abbot.

1101
01:37:34,147 --> 01:37:36,477
- Abbot slaughterhouse?
- Yeah. You heard of it?

1102
01:37:36,602 --> 01:37:39,326
I wanna redesign it. I went there,
but they wouldn't let me meet with them.

1103
01:37:39,451 --> 01:37:41,684
But I have several ideas
about how to make a new facility

1104
01:37:41,809 --> 01:37:44,373
that will be much more
humane and efficient.

1105
01:37:44,843 --> 01:37:47,694
I guess you just have
to meet my husband then.

1106
01:37:48,122 --> 01:37:50,563
How wonderful
that we bumped into each other.

1107
01:37:53,862 --> 01:37:56,537
A door opened and I went through it.

1108
01:37:56,663 --> 01:37:57,990
Yes, you did.

1109
01:37:58,772 --> 01:37:59,972
And I held it.

1110
01:38:07,256 --> 01:38:09,621
This looks like an airport for cows.

1111
01:38:11,415 --> 01:38:13,666
I didn't mean that as a compliment.

1112
01:38:14,015 --> 01:38:16,016
And conveyor belts for cattle?

1113
01:38:17,375 --> 01:38:20,381
Do you have any idea
what the cost is on this?

1114
01:38:21,112 --> 01:38:23,987
And you've got
solid walls and floors.

1115
01:38:24,885 --> 01:38:27,283
We have those slatted for a reason.

1116
01:38:27,806 --> 01:38:29,286
- It's cheaper.
- I'm sorry.

1117
01:38:29,455 --> 01:38:32,500
It's clear you don't have the experience
to design something like this.

1118
01:38:32,767 --> 01:38:34,520
The walls are solid so the cattle

1119
01:38:34,645 --> 01:38:37,528
won't be distracted
by light or movement outside.

1120
01:38:37,654 --> 01:38:39,062
They balk at unexpected things.

1121
01:38:39,187 --> 01:38:41,697
I'm sure that's nice for the cattle,
but the cost, miss...

1122
01:38:41,822 --> 01:38:45,812
How much money does it cost you
to pay handlers to prod the cattle along

1123
01:38:45,980 --> 01:38:48,378
and then hold 'em back
when they stampede?

1124
01:38:48,503 --> 01:38:51,695
How many times a day do your chutes stop
because of pile-ups?

1125
01:38:52,182 --> 01:38:55,756
How many cows break a leg
and bring everything to a halt?

1126
01:38:55,881 --> 01:38:58,189
With my system,
there'd be none of that.

1127
01:38:58,314 --> 01:39:00,929
There'd be a steady calm flow.

1128
01:39:01,790 --> 01:39:04,903
That sounds great, but you don't have
any idea of whether it'll work.

1129
01:39:05,028 --> 01:39:06,028
But I do.

1130
01:39:06,552 --> 01:39:09,807
I'm like Nikola Tesla or Thomas Edison,
I know it will work

1131
01:39:09,932 --> 01:39:12,689
'cause I've been through it
a thousand times in my head.

1132
01:39:12,814 --> 01:39:14,980
I can see a chute
just as the cattle will

1133
01:39:15,148 --> 01:39:16,816
because my autism lets me do it.

1134
01:39:17,432 --> 01:39:19,612
I can walk through a plan
in my mind,

1135
01:39:19,883 --> 01:39:22,797
examining every beam
and every rivet.

1136
01:39:23,112 --> 01:39:26,763
You just see a plan,
but I'm walkin' through the whole plant.

1137
01:39:28,523 --> 01:39:32,043
Okay, the cattle go
through series of solid curves.

1138
01:39:32,168 --> 01:39:35,014
The floor is solid too... grooved.

1139
01:39:35,575 --> 01:39:37,775
The chute gets smaller,
but the cattle won't mind.

1140
01:39:37,900 --> 01:39:39,368
They don't see any danger.

1141
01:39:39,493 --> 01:39:42,058
They think
they're just gettin' into another truck.

1142
01:39:42,569 --> 01:39:45,062
The stairway leads
them gently upwards.

1143
01:39:45,187 --> 01:39:48,000
The floor becomes a conveyor.

1144
01:39:48,125 --> 01:39:50,720
A rest rises up to meet their chest

1145
01:39:50,845 --> 01:39:52,896
so they're comfortably carried.

1146
01:39:54,259 --> 01:39:56,180
They'll be very calm.

1147
01:40:07,753 --> 01:40:10,813
<i>Nature is cruel,
but we don't have to be.</i>

1148
01:40:12,089 --> 01:40:14,116
We owe them some respect.

1149
01:40:18,052 --> 01:40:20,536
I touched the first cow
as it was being stunned.

1150
01:40:21,617 --> 01:40:24,187
In a few seconds, it was gonna be
just another piece of beef, but...

1151
01:40:24,313 --> 01:40:27,179
In that moment,
it was still an individual.

1152
01:40:28,510 --> 01:40:29,560
It was calm

1153
01:40:32,825 --> 01:40:34,375
and then it was gone.

1154
01:40:36,228 --> 01:40:39,236
I became aware
of how precious life was.

1155
01:40:40,035 --> 01:40:43,267
And I thought about death
and I felt close to God.

1156
01:40:47,869 --> 01:40:50,326
I don't want my thoughts
to die with me.

1157
01:40:50,451 --> 01:40:52,452
I want to have done something.

1158
01:40:54,279 --> 01:40:56,380
Thank you for inviting me.

1159
01:40:57,059 --> 01:40:59,606
You were the one person
I wanted here.

1160
01:41:00,061 --> 01:41:02,883
Other people would have been overwhelmed
by what they were seeing.

1161
01:41:03,008 --> 01:41:04,416
It would have confused them.

1162
01:41:04,541 --> 01:41:07,814
I knew you would be the only one
able to sense what was really going on,

1163
01:41:07,982 --> 01:41:11,027
who could feel
what I was trying to accomplish.

1164
01:41:11,195 --> 01:41:13,198
There are a lot of things
I can't understand,

1165
01:41:13,323 --> 01:41:15,925
but I still want my life
to have meaning.

1166
01:41:25,285 --> 01:41:28,516
I don't know that I want to hear
from any more experts.

1167
01:41:30,823 --> 01:41:33,966
<i>If you will please let me finish.
Will you please let me finish?</i>

1168
01:41:34,092 --> 01:41:37,529
<i>With intensive psychotherapy,
an autistic child can be treated...</i>

1169
01:41:37,776 --> 01:41:41,198
But the Rimland report plainly shows
autism isn't a psychological problem.

1170
01:41:41,716 --> 01:41:44,244
Calm down.
Calm done, sweetie.

1171
01:41:44,874 --> 01:41:47,414
<i>It would be better
if you could get her to sit calmly.</i>

1172
01:41:47,582 --> 01:41:48,753
<i>Try to control her.</i>

1173
01:41:49,419 --> 01:41:52,506
<i>But we were told self-stimming is good.
It eventually calms them.</i>

1174
01:41:52,674 --> 01:41:54,717
<i>Self-stimming is self-comforting.</i>

1175
01:41:54,947 --> 01:41:57,221
<i>Self-stimulation...
Rocking, spinning, rolling...</i>

1176
01:41:57,740 --> 01:41:59,641
Well, I think spinning is good.

1177
01:42:00,112 --> 01:42:01,413
And rolling too.

1178
01:42:02,055 --> 01:42:05,972
Self-stimulation does seem
to eventually calm the nervous system.

1179
01:42:06,152 --> 01:42:09,210
It can be a way to compensate
for not being held.

1180
01:42:09,335 --> 01:42:11,442
And being held
by another person is scary,

1181
01:42:11,567 --> 01:42:14,741
but rolling
or being held by surfaces

1182
01:42:14,866 --> 01:42:17,991
produces the calming effect
that ordinary children get from a hug.

1183
01:42:18,257 --> 01:42:19,808
How old's your child?

1184
01:42:21,427 --> 01:42:23,328
Well, I don't have children.

1185
01:42:24,576 --> 01:42:25,927
No, I'm autistic.

1186
01:42:27,121 --> 01:42:29,723
And I need the sensation
of being hugged.

1187
01:42:30,521 --> 01:42:32,640
And I've developed a machine
that I get into

1188
01:42:32,765 --> 01:42:35,115
and hugs me
and I'm different afterwards.

1189
01:42:35,240 --> 01:42:36,541
I'm more social.

1190
01:42:37,176 --> 01:42:39,488
Well, I didn't speak
until I was four

1191
01:42:39,613 --> 01:42:43,619
and now I have a B.A. and a masters
and I'm studying for my doctorate.

1192
01:42:46,754 --> 01:42:48,589
Please don't shout!
Please!

1193
01:42:49,420 --> 01:42:52,678
Most autistic people
are very sensitive

1194
01:42:52,846 --> 01:42:54,397
to sounds and colors.

1195
01:42:55,716 --> 01:42:58,478
Over-stimulation hurts.

1196
01:42:59,668 --> 01:43:03,473
People talkin' too much at once,
you know, can cause us to panic.

1197
01:43:03,598 --> 01:43:05,199
How did you get cured?

1198
01:43:06,218 --> 01:43:09,828
Well, I'm not cured.
I'll always be autistic.

1199
01:43:10,192 --> 01:43:14,140
My mother refused to believe
that I wouldn't speak.

1200
01:43:14,378 --> 01:43:18,112
And when I learned to speak,
she made me go to school.

1201
01:43:18,365 --> 01:43:20,492
And in school and at home,

1202
01:43:21,013 --> 01:43:23,564
manners and rules
were really important.

1203
01:43:23,689 --> 01:43:25,490
They were pounded into me.

1204
01:43:25,718 --> 01:43:26,819
I was lucky.

1205
01:43:26,944 --> 01:43:28,815
All these things worked for me.

1206
01:43:29,221 --> 01:43:32,237
Everyone worked hard
to make sure that I was engaged.

1207
01:43:32,362 --> 01:43:35,672
I mean, they knew I was different,
but not less.

1208
01:43:35,797 --> 01:43:37,245
You know, I had a gift.

1209
01:43:37,413 --> 01:43:39,078
I could see the world in a new way.

1210
01:43:39,204 --> 01:43:42,806
I could see details
that other people were blind to.

1211
01:43:44,200 --> 01:43:47,590
My mother pushed me
to become self-sufficient.

1212
01:43:47,715 --> 01:43:50,430
I worked summers at my aunt's ranch.

1213
01:43:50,635 --> 01:43:53,226
I went to boarding school
and college

1214
01:43:53,394 --> 01:43:56,314
and those things
were uncomfortable for me at first,

1215
01:43:56,661 --> 01:43:59,562
but they helped me
to open doors to new worlds.

1216
01:43:59,899 --> 01:44:01,299
Excuse me, please,

1217
01:44:02,035 --> 01:44:03,951
but we want to hear everything.

1218
01:44:28,906 --> 01:44:30,407
<i>Are you a scientist?</i>

1219
01:44:30,965 --> 01:44:33,991
- <i>You cannot hit people.</i>
- <i>Think you can figure it out?</i>

1220
01:44:34,187 --> 01:44:36,497
<i>Four, three, two, one.</i>

1221
01:44:36,623 --> 01:44:38,687
<i>I have a pen and a clipboard.</i>

1222
01:44:38,812 --> 01:44:41,435
- <i>Think of it as a door.</i>
- <i>Just take one knock to the head.</i>

1223
01:44:41,560 --> 01:44:44,464
<i>I don't understand
why people are cruel for no reason!</i>

1224
01:44:44,589 --> 01:44:46,489
<i>You have a very special mind.</i>

1225
01:44:46,614 --> 01:44:48,735
<i>You see the world
in ways that others can't.</i>

1226
01:44:48,861 --> 01:44:51,016
<i>Miss Grandin, this is a masterpiece.</i>

1227
01:44:51,141 --> 01:44:53,549
<i>A door opened and I went through it.</i>

1228
01:44:53,811 --> 01:44:56,459
<i>Yes, you did, and I held it.</i>

1229
01:45:01,067 --> 01:45:02,518
I'm Temple Grandin.

1230
01:45:06,610 --> 01:45:09,368
{\Temple is a professor
at Colorado State University}

1231
